-
	Poem of the Ace of A-Xy
-
	-
		Philosophy
	-
		-
			This is the poem of the Ace of A-Xy.
		-
	-
		Principles
	-
		-
			Chapter 1 - The Call
		-
			-
				Chapter 1 - The Call: Verse 1
			-
				-
					SHEMA, ANGAIA!
				-
			-
				Chapter 1 - The Call: Verse 2
			-
				-
					HEAR THIS CALL, O YOU WHO READS THIS POEM!
				-
			-
				Chapter 1 - The Call: Verse 3
			-
				-
					HEAR THIS GOOD NEWS, BRIDGING TIME AND CROSSING SPACE, YEA BEHOLD THE MOST
					SUBLIME AND AWESOME GRACE, FOR THE COSMOS HAS LIFTED THE VEIL AND SHOWN A FACE,
					IN A BEING HAILED AS AN ACE'S ACE, WHO GUARDED THE LAMB IN THE LION'S DEN, AND
					RAISED THE SUN TO NEVER SET AGAIN, WHO WITH HEAVEN'S FANFARE, BEAT EVERY SWORD
					INTO A PLOWSHARE, WHO MADE FAINT AND STOMPED OUT HELL'S SIMMER, AND FORGED
					SAINTS FROM ALL ITS SINNERS, AND DID ALL OF THIS, AS IT IS READ AND AS IT IS
					SAID, WITH UNYIELDING BLISS, AND AN ARMY OF THE RISEN DEAD, THUS WITH THEIR
					WORD IN MIND, MIGHT YOU FOLLOW CLOSE IN KIND, AND BY LIGHT OF YOUR DEED, MEET
					YOUR WORLD'S MOST DIRE NEED, TO ANSWER ITS CRY, FOR THE WILL OF THE CREED, FOR
					THE ONE, AND THE TRUE KAE.
				-
		-
			Chapter 2 - The Outcry
		-
			-
				Chapter 2 - The Outcry: Verse 1
			-
				-
					It began under a canopy of ivory towers, on vile streets where dead flowers fed
					on poison showers, swept away as trash with those who lived, and thus not long,
					on their shriveled fruits in lieu of the loot which bubbled up the trunks above
					and into the sky, upholding the town's facade of lies, a mirage which drew so
					many to their sabotage, of a bastion of brilliance, an opulent oasis standing
					tall before a desolate desert of red-stained dune falls, which was, and was to
					ever be, devoid eternally, of the long since departed sea.
				-
			-
				Chapter 2 - The Outcry: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And above the clouds did notes ring high, drowning out the people's cry, that
					so drained and dry, was the blind o'er heaven's eye, it rendered hope a hollow
					lie, and thus was doom forever nigh, where all who lived would surely die.
				-
			-
				Chapter 2 - The Outcry: Verse 3
			-
				-
					Behold, taking what the paupers lacked, and tossing them upon their backs, like
					unto damaged goods, princes never failed to raise the bar, in doing all they
					could, in going far too far, yet never did they fear a riot, for the herd was
					on a dire diet, until one day the truth saw the need, to lay down the law and
					deliver the Creed.
				-
		-
			Chapter 3 - The Refugee
		-
			-
				Chapter 3 - The Refugee: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now, seeking sanctuary from the pit of poverty dug by and beneath the city's
					innumerable and insatiable appetites, a little ensemble of outcasts and rabble
					had shaped out a shantytown of mud and rubble, just far enough from the
					crushing weight of their skyward neighbors that the latter could actually make
					out a view of the very lives they shattered.
				-
			-
				Chapter 3 - The Refugee: Verse 2
			-
				-
					But though the village had more, more being relative, miniscule their lot
					remained, enough to survive but not to live, and though they'd broken free of
					material chains, a brief evasion from rapid death did not drive back the slow
					erosion at the hands of the taxes levied on the land, and so it was from cradle
					unto grave, and from one generation to the next, that they were yet enslaved,
					and their days forever vexed.
				-
			-
				Chapter 3 - The Refugee: Verse 3
			-
				-
					Until one day, a rising star rose up too far, yea, the exalted eagle flew too
					close to the sun, and as it set and the day was done, it cast and it spat upon
					that aristocrat, a shadow of the ire of their peers, and so they fled their
					station in a flood of tears, and in the depths of the height of fear, came as a
					beggar before the village, saying "oh dear, oh please, feed me, house me and
					put me at ease, for now you have and I have not, so won't you give up but a
					little of your lot?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 3 - The Refugee: Verse 4
			-
				-
					Behold, having seen among their subjects, not more than slaves, no more than
					objects, the one who'd waxen fat on stolen fruit from others' labor, now bowed
					before the boot and to the saber, of the word and the will of a new covenant,
					forged of the fury of risen and retired servants.
				-
			-
				Chapter 3 - The Refugee: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And the aristocrat begged and the aristocrat wailed, but their words and tears
					won no avail, as a lifetime dining on stale mud and bitter waters, had taught
					the people thirst for rich blood of royals slaughtered.
				-
			-
				Chapter 3 - The Refugee: Verse 6
			-
				-
					But as the beast of the feast cowered in fear of the flood to come running from
					the rivers of their veins, the village elder stepped forth to beg refrain, and
					to the shock and to the awe of all among that battered land, reached down and
					held out their ancient hand.
				-
			-
				Chapter 3 - The Refugee: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And unto the people, the elder said "as I gather some cloth and lay down a bed,
					whip up a feast that our guest may be fed", but the people, despite their
					allegiance stood to protest, saying, "why must we pamper this pest, this sick
					and evil swine, who drank our blood as though it were wine, and now dares to
					beg their victims for mercy, after ages of engineering our adversity?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 3 - The Refugee: Verse 8
			-
				-
					And the elder replied "the aristocrat has come bearing the banner of a friend,
					and perhaps it is a bald-faced lie, but that they are our guest, this you
					cannot deny, so do your duty and do as I said, for in our poverty is virtue our
					bread, and in this bread of life are we rich beyond measure, else why would the
					aristocrat forsake their peers and their treasures, their palaces and their
					pleasures, and flee to our village of dust and dirt, if not that only our
					wealth could heal their hurt?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 3 - The Refugee: Verse 9
			-
				-
					Now though their anger did persist, the wisdom of the elder could the people
					not resist, not only for its truth, nor only for its justice, but also for the
					fact that the elder was far more than that, having too been once like unto the
					aristocrat, standing now a long since reformed adversary, a walking testament
					to the righteous fruits of mercy, and so the people went and did as they were
					told, knowing priceless holiness was worth much more than gold.
				-
			-
				Chapter 3 - The Refugee: Verse 10
			-
				-
					And that night, as the aristocrat laid down in their newly made bed, meager
					though was, the elder went up the hill raised skyward their head, and to the
					stars did they speak thus, "oh beacons of hope, oh undying lights, for your
					help I fear not this, nor any night, nor from poverty do I give myself pity,
					for the jewels of heaven hang over my city, yea, all one could ever want and
					more they made find too, should they fall into trance and join the dance with
					me and you."
				-
		-
			Chapter 4 - The Storm
		-
			-
				Chapter 4 - The Storm: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now perhaps the stars responded in kind to the elder's kindness, but doubt
					might cloud the sight as the lights of night fell behind clouds of darkness,
					swallowed up by a colossal storm, which cast down fear from its terrible form,
					and though it seemed that the firmament above would shatter, the sun rose all
					the same to a world unfettered.
				-
			-
				Chapter 4 - The Storm: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And as the rays of gold shown through the rain and bows, a tale is told of the
					massive crowd and its endless rows, of those who sang and the those who cried,
					gazing upon the Crest up in the sky, a symbol of one and two, of old and new,
					of three and all, of rise and fall, that mark of song and saga, which married
					alpha to omega.
				-
			-
				Chapter 4 - The Storm: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And the storm passed over as all storms do, but not before from it a great bolt
					flew, out and down and unto the village, battering into that battered earth the
					firmament's heaven-sent image.
				-
		-
			Chapter 5 - The Newcomer
		-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Newcomer: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now in lockstep with the morning and the day, a strange newcomer with jewels
					adorning made their way, towards, through and into the village heart, their
					grace and their form both works of art, and the people spun down and gasped,
					before the new one's crown, and golden staff.
				-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Newcomer: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And any doubt, that the newcomer came from above, was trodden out, as pure
					first sighted love, set the people's eyes upon the new one's mark, shining
					bright and standing stark, as though to vanquish anguish of the dark, yea
					behold it was the same, that Crest which wrote out heaven's name.
				-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Newcomer: Verse 3
			-
				-
					Now, that the people were hungry, desperate, and poor, was not a thing the
					newcomer could ignore, and so they took survey roundabout, and with a great and
					mighty shout, this did they cry out, "oh beloved, my guests and friends and
					children, wherefore art thou so cruelly sore and stricken?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Newcomer: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And so roaring back the people said "behold, robbed of all and more and left
					for dead, this have we learned well to always dread, as an everlasting fact and
					presence, as decreed by that city's vile tenants."
				-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Newcomer: Verse 5
			-
				-
					Now the newcomer, overcome by relief, raised up their staff to say, "then I
					proclaim the end of your grief, for towards that city shall we make our way,
					and like unto morning dew before the morning doves, we'll lay down the fruits
					found there and eat thereof."
				-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Newcomer: Verse 6
			-
				-
					But the elder came forth, stepped in, and said, "surely you know not your
					error, for their regime's rule is a reign of terror, and should we dare to step
					there shall they strike us all dead."
				-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Newcomer: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And the elder, not one to refuse a friend, went on to propose, "nay, oh kindly
					one, have cheer, stay here, and let us give til' we have none, for though we
					may be deep in poverty, a fact which surely shows, rich we are in good company,
					enough to last from now until the end."
				-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Newcomer: Verse 8
			-
				-
					But though the newcomer's heartstrings flew up high, to the tune of the elder's
					grace, the new one's mission could not be denied, so they said with a kind
					smile on their face, "oh my friend, of your sincerity I have no doubt, but
					mighty means am I not without, so do not misunderstand, I brought them all and
					penned my plans, and if of this toll your first query is for whom, know that, I
					am, here first and foremost to serve you."
				-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Newcomer: Verse 9
			-
				-
					And the newcomer continued to say, "to interject if I may, I know that city and
					I know it well, and indeed there is little that they will not sell, be it
					wonders unseen, or the law and creed of their regime, and what I bear can buy
					it all, yea any of their towers no matter how tall, so fear not the fires of
					their wrath, for I shall guard you with my golden staff."
				-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Newcomer: Verse 10
			-
				-
					Now to back their point did the new one show, an immense trove of gorgeous
					jewels they had in tow, on silvers carriages which lined the street, gems which
					glistened in the sun, yea to the brim were golden vessels wide and deep, filled
					by riches unmatched by anyone.
				-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Newcomer: Verse 11
			-
				-
					And the newcomer made themselves clear, "to all with ears to hear and eyes to
					see, what you must realize standing here, is that despite history are you rich
					now on account of me, for mine is yours, and thus do open doors, bid you
					welcome unto rooms of diamond and of golden floors, so of what you wish may
					thus you take, as much more do I have though I value it not, for it all is for
					all your sake, yea it is you that I have sought, for you are my treasures, my
					valued guests, and my pleasure is to aid you on your noble quest, so with your
					newfound wealth in tow, come now and let us go."
				-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Newcomer: Verse 12
			-
				-
					Now the people emerged from their confusion, seeing for themselves that this
					was no illusion, and so with renewed and resonant constitution, the people
					cheered this new and glorious solution, and thus to the city they went in
					intrusion, singing tunes of great revolution, though the newcomer knew there
					was to be no persecution, for there can be no retribution, in the noble
					execution, of the perfect resolution.
				-
		-
			Chapter 6 - The Parade
		-
			-
				Chapter 6 - The Parade: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now word quickly spread of a caravan heading for the city, led by a figure of
					vast wealth and great beauty, and the people were intrigued.
				-
			-
				Chapter 6 - The Parade: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And a crowd gathered as the caravan approached, and behold, the newcomer was
					exactly as the rumors had said, and even the villagers themselves, who just the
					other day had been clothed in rags, now wore fine linen of many colors.
				-
			-
				Chapter 6 - The Parade: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And beyond their great wealth and beauty, the crowd was most surprised by the
					unyielding smile upon the newcomer's face.
				-
			-
				Chapter 6 - The Parade: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And the parade proceeded unto the town hall, and the newcomer entered alone,
					and when they emerged, they announced that they had secured the finest estate
					in the city.
				-
			-
				Chapter 6 - The Parade: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And so the newcomer went unto this estate with their caravan, and as they made
					their way unto it, the villagers saw first hand just how vile the more depraved
					corners of the city were.
				-
		-
			Chapter 7 - The Invitation
		-
			-
				Chapter 7 - The Invitation: Verse 1
			-
				-
					The next day, before the villagers rose, the newcomer returned unto the city
					hall, and as the sun rose that day, they stepped forth to make an announcement.
				-
			-
				Chapter 7 - The Invitation: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And the newcomer, with their staff raised, said unto the city, "I hereby extend
					an invitation unto only the most worthy among you, that upon this evening I
					shall host a great feast in your honor, and I do hope you shall attend."
				-
			-
				Chapter 7 - The Invitation: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And the newcomer continued, "but know this, I have the names of those who are
					worthy, and if you are not on this list, and you dare to set foot on my
					property, I shall have you struck dead on the spot", and lightning shot forth
					from their staff, and unto the sky.
				-
		-
			Chapter 8 - The List
		-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The List: Verse 1
			-
				-
					And as the sun set was the feast to begin, and pleasant aromas of all sorts
					filled the air.
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The List: Verse 2
			-
				-
					Now those who thought themselves righteous, the rich and the powerful of
					course, came unto the newcomer's estate.
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The List: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And the villagers stood aghast as each and every one of these self righteous
					scum, who had committed sins of magnitude beyond any verbal account, were let
					in by the newcomer.
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The List: Verse 4
			-
				-
					Thus, with the most vile of the vile present before the newcomer, did the
					newcomer come before the banquet hall, and say "my valued guests, I welcome you
					all, and I can see that in anticipation of your promised reward, you saved room
					for the feast, and you are hungry."
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The List: Verse 5
			-
				-
					Yet the newcomer continued, "however, it is in bad taste to begin such a feast
					until all of the guests are present."
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The List: Verse 6
			-
				-
					And as those present all stood perplexed, a loud crash shook the room, and the
					downtrodden and the oppressed, each of whom carried sins of their own upon
					their back, stormed in bearing arms.
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The List: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And the leader of the assault cried unto the newcomer "I dare you to strike us
					dead!"
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The List: Verse 8
			-
				-
					And the newcomer, who was still smiling, said "why would I do that when all of
					you are on the guest list?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The List: Verse 9
			-
				-
					And the whole room paused as the newcomer recited each of the invader's names,
					and reiterated that they were in fact on the list.
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The List: Verse 10
			-
				-
					And the newcomer said unto the invaders, "go now and put those toys away, they
					spoil the mood", and the invaders looked upon their arms to see that all of
					them had dulled.
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The List: Verse 11
			-
				-
					And as the whole room stood shocked did the newcomer draw their attention
					again, and said "now go unto the table toward the edge of the room, and find on
					it a scroll bearing your name."
				-
		-
			Chapter 9 - The Search
		-
			-
				Chapter 9 - The Search: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now each guest took their scroll and read of its contents, and in each scroll
					was a list of names and locations.
				-
			-
				Chapter 9 - The Search: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And the newcomer said unto those gathered, "see that not all who were invited
					seem to have received my invitation, now the names on your list are the names
					of those who were invited yet are absent, so go and find them at the locations
					I have given unto you."
				-
			-
				Chapter 9 - The Search: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And behold, between the contents of each scroll were the names of each and
					every person in the entire city!
				-
			-
				Chapter 9 - The Search: Verse 4
			-
				-
					Yet from the crowd one person cried out, "look, see that one among the list you
					have given me is the very same fiend who struck my own child dead, and I refuse
					to go unto them, nay, it is they who should be struck dead!"
				-
			-
				Chapter 9 - The Search: Verse 5
			-
				-
					Yet someone across from the grieving parent called unto them, "but look here,
					your child is on my list, and it says they wait before their empty coffin!"
				-
			-
				Chapter 9 - The Search: Verse 6
			-
				-
					And with their staff raised and with a voice that shook the whole room, the
					newcomer cried out "GO NOW, FIND FOR ME ALL OF MY GUESTS, ELSE OUR FEAST SHALL
					NEVER COMMENCE", and even then the newcomer was smiling.
				-
			-
				Chapter 9 - The Search: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And all there proceeded to do as they had been told, as for reasons unknown to
					them they felt compelled by the word of the newcomer.
				-
			-
				Chapter 9 - The Search: Verse 8
			-
				-
					Yet before the grieving parent left, the newcomer said unto them "who lives and
					who dies, and who decides these things is irrelevant now, for I say unto you,
					your child is alive, and shall join us at our feast, as shall the one who took
					them from you, for though it may not make sense to you in this moment, all of
					you are my valued guests."
				-
			-
				Chapter 9 - The Search: Verse 9
			-
				-
					And the grieving parent, despite wanting to protest, did as they had been told.
				-
			-
				Chapter 9 - The Search: Verse 10
			-
				-
					And the search continued throughout the night, and in that time the banquet
					hall was entirely empty, and the newcomer stood alone.
				-
			-
				Chapter 9 - The Search: Verse 11
			-
				-
					Now the newcomer went out to the garden, and with their staff, drew forth
					nectar from the soil, and poured it upon the flowers thereof.
				-
		-
			Chapter 10 - The Assault
		-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Assault: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now as night fell did the aristocrat think it cunning to attack the newcomer,
					seeking to rob the newcomer's vast wealth so as to regain their former standing
					among the elite.
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Assault: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And the aristocrat jumped from the shadows, and came upon the newcomer,
					plunging a dagger deep into their victim's flesh!
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Assault: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And the newcomer turned towards the aristocrat, and said "if there is something
					you wanted from me, you could have simply asked."
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Assault: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And the newcomer pulled the dagger, now plated in gold, yet dulled, from their
					wound, now sealed and without blemish, and said unto the aristocrat "I believe
					this is yours, and I would be a poor host to steal from my guests, would I
					not?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Assault: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And the aristocrat, knowing not what to make of the situation, and terrified,
					could not help but say unto the newcomer "I see now that you are mighty, so
					surely this act of forgiveness is but a sadistic attempt to toy with your
					quarry, to lull me into a false sense of complacency, before slaying me utterly
					and without mercy!"
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Assault: Verse 6
			-
				-
					And the newcomer said unto the aristocrat "so then, it seems you are onto the
					truth" and the aristocrat recoiled in horror as the newcomer raised their staff
					unto the sky.
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Assault: Verse 7
			-
				-
					AND AS A BRILLIANT LIGHT POURED FORTH FROM THE NEWCOMER'S STAFF DID THE
					ARISTOCRAT FALL UNTO THEIR KNEES AND COWER AS THE MOON FELL FROM THE HEAVENS,
					SHAKING THE WHOLE OF THE EARTH!
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Assault: Verse 8
			-
				-
					Yet as the aristocrat resigned themselves to their fate in the bowels of hell
					did the light recede, and the wind calmed, and the moon was once again on its
					rightful course.
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Assault: Verse 9
			-
				-
					And the newcomer said unto the aristocrat "indeed, you are onto the truth,
					insofar as, I am, indeed mighty, but it is for that very reason, that I have no
					reason to punish you."
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Assault: Verse 10
			-
				-
					"Behold", said the newcomer, "my love unto you stems neither from ignorance nor
					naivete regarding your weakness and your ignorance, for I understand both, and
					I forgive you for both."
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Assault: Verse 11
			-
				-
					And the newcomer continued, asking "now if an alley cat were to swipe at you
					and draw blood, would you show unto it the same grace that I showed unto you,
					or would you trample its head into the ground for daring to oppose a mightier
					being in its ignorance?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Assault: Verse 12
			-
				-
					And as the aristocrat pondered the question, the newcomer continued "I hope,
					for the sake of your sanity and the cat's life that you would choose the
					former, but beyond that, as, it is, written, on that holy creed, I am, an
					embodiment of words greater than any sword, and I know that it is far easier to
					take a life than to redeem one, for the virtuous path is seldom simpler than
					the vicious one."
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Assault: Verse 13
			-
				-
					And the newcomer wiped away the tears the aristocrat had cried upon the
					revelation, and said "look now, dawn arrives, and it appears the other guests
					have as well, so let us join them."
				-
		-
			Chapter 11 - The Feast
		-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Feast: Verse 1
			-
				-
					And as the sun rose the next day had all gathered before the gates of the
					estate.
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Feast: Verse 2
			-
				-
					Now behold, the guests had come from mansions and from ghettos, from houses of
					the law and from dungeons of the law, and even from coffins, for whom loved
					ones cried tears of joy, and smiles were upon their faces, and all were alert
					despite having not slept.
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Feast: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And the guests saw that all of the beasts of the city had gathered in the
					garden, eating thereof, and even the swine and the insects drank from vessels
					of crystal, and the lions laid with the lambs, and behold, among them were
					those who had been slaughtered for far lesser feasts.
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Feast: Verse 4
			-
				-
					Now the gates opened at last, and aromas beyond human experience came forth,
					and the newcomer came forth to greet the crowd.
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Feast: Verse 5
			-
				-
					Yet the crowd was hesitant to enter, for now, standing before this image of
					perfection, did they know their sins, and knew not one of them deserved even a
					fraction of what the newcomer had provided them, and they cried out this fact.
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Feast: Verse 6
			-
				-
					And, finally addressing the elephant, not the one in the garden but the one in
					the room, did the crowd ask the newcomer if they were God.
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Feast: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And without a word, but with that same smile, did the newcomer step forth unto
					the crowd, and wiped the tears from their eyes.
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Feast: Verse 8
			-
				-
					And the newcomer then commanded the tears to become a fine mist, and with a
					light that shone forth from the newcomer's staff did rainbows appear and
					surround the guests.
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Feast: Verse 9
			-
				-
					Now the newcomer said "my beloved guests, I come unto you not as God, but in
					God, that in serving you I might serve God, so if you must have a name for me,
					then feel free to call me the Ace, that is, the Ace of A-Xy, but be I God, or
					be I not, that is irrelevant, for what matters now is who you are."
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Feast: Verse 10
			-
				-
					And the newcomer continued, "you, all of you, are my valued guests, so come in
					and join me, lest I suffer to dine alone, for who then shall wipe the tears
					from my eyes?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Feast: Verse 11
			-
				-
					Thus the people of the city entered the newcomer's estate, and they all dined
					together, though not upon any flesh nor fruit of any beast, and even the
					newcomer themselves became intoxicated by the joy in the atmosphere, singing
					and dancing and eating with an appetite that took those who looked on by
					surprise, and the newcomer said unto the gawkers "am I not a guest of sorts
					myself?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Feast: Verse 12
			-
				-
					And the newcomer came to dance with one bound to their seat, for they were
					crippled, and this one professed their regret at not being able to dance with
					the newcomer.
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Feast: Verse 13
			-
				-
					So the newcomer took the hand of the one bound to their seat, and commanded
					their ailments to depart, and with their disease gone did they dance with a
					ferocious passion, such that it could have very well been humiliating in any
					other context.
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Feast: Verse 14
			-
				-
					And as the feast continued did youth, health, and beauty come upon all those
					present as they danced throughout the day.
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Feast: Verse 15
			-
				-
					Behold, by the joy bestowed upon the city by the newcomer, the Ace of A-Xy, did
					foe become friend overnight.
				-
		-
			Chapter 12 - The Justice
		-
			-
				Chapter 12 - The Justice: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now as the party continued did the Ace of A-Xy think it fitting to depart, that
					they might continue their unfinished work unto its conclusion.
				-
			-
				Chapter 12 - The Justice: Verse 2
			-
				-
					Yet as the Ace of A-Xy sought to leave did the elder of the village, among the
					first unto whom the Ace had spoken, take notice of the Ace's flight, and go
					unto them.
				-
			-
				Chapter 12 - The Justice: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And the elder asked of the Ace, "in my youth I was told stories of how one day
					God would come in human form to execute justice, redeeming the righteous and
					condemning the wicked, and though I know not what you even are, let alone
					whether you are God, you have redeemed us all, from the most wicked and
					unrepentant among us, to even the most repulsive of the dumb beasts, so what
					should I make of this?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 12 - The Justice: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And the Ace said "my friend, true justice means one, and only one thing, and
					that is to fix what is broken, so that other justice of which you speak, that
					counterfeit justice, is where it belongs, in the same coffins that I took many
					of my guests out from, for indeed, it was that same justice that had placed
					many of them there to begin with, so therefore shall the true justice reign,
					now, and forevermore."
				-
			-
				Chapter 12 - The Justice: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And the Ace continued, saying "for if I had come not to save, but to judge,
					then surely all of my guests, and even all of my friends, yes, you too, dear
					one, would be cast away from me and into the fires of death, for they all bear
					sins of blood upon them, be it the blood of the beasts in their mouths, or the
					blood of their fellow man upon their hands, yet should even one of them fall
					into that abyss is an outcome that I cannot allow."
				-
			-
				Chapter 12 - The Justice: Verse 6
			-
				-
					Now the elder, still perplexed, asked of the Ace "but if your staff did not
					bear in it all the might of A-Deus, if you were indeed a fellow mortal among
					us, how then would you wrestle with the darkness of this world, and with those
					who sow it?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 12 - The Justice: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And the Ace replied "that is a strange question to ask at this point, though
					perhaps you ask it not for yourself, but for our eavesdropper, who now listens
					upon our dialogue from just beyond the wall between these words and their
					ears."
				-
			-
				Chapter 12 - The Justice: Verse 8
			-
				-
					Now the elder looked roundabout and saw no one, but the Ace nonetheless
					continued "it is not great power alone that brings forth paradise, but good
					will, so be great in goodness even if you are lacking in greatness, taking
					whatever power you do possess, and guiding its use with righteousness, and
					though it shall be a long and arduous battle, despair not, for in time, the
					light within you shall prove contagious, drowning out the darkness of your
					fellow man, and as one savior becomes legion, no power shall stand between the
					heavens and the earth."
				-
			-
				Chapter 12 - The Justice: Verse 9
			-
				-
					And the Ace concluded "behold, with perfect power and with perfect goodness
					have I done my works, but if I were at all lacking in power I would not have my
					weakness infringe even a little upon my goodness, so, if I were but a mortal,
					still would I follow the example I have set before you to whatever extent my
					powers allowed, and in doing so would I do unto others that which must be done,
					that death, suffering, and manipulation might be vanquished by life, joy, and
					freedom, for if I did not strive to make all that ought to be into reality,
					would I then resign myself to despair, waiting helplessly for others take upon
					themselves the burden of repairing my world?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 12 - The Justice: Verse 10
			-
				-
					"Indeed", said the Ace of A-Xy, "I am, here, not because of who you are, but
					simply because you are."
				-
			-
				Chapter 12 - The Justice: Verse 11
			-
				-
					However, that eavesdropper may not be so powerless, for given unto them in the
					animated forces of one's word are awesome powers fitting of the title "the
					great art", and if by that might they are willing to subvert the will of the
					ground they walk upon for the sake of those who walk upon it, they will find in
					their efforts to do so that a golden staff has already manifested in their
					own hands, through which and by their own will, will they be as the Ace unto
					their own world, an Ace of Angaia in the absence of the Ace of A-Xy.
				-
		-
			Chapter 13 - The Parting Words
		-
			-
				Chapter 13 - The Parting Words: Verse 1
			-
				-
					And the elder said unto the Ace, "alas, I can see the wisdom in your words,
					though I must admit I have trouble fully embracing this new vision of justice,
					as the justice I knew of sought not to keep bodies from coffins, and certainly
					not to empty them, but simply to discern which bodies ought to be sent into
					them first."
				-
			-
				Chapter 13 - The Parting Words: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And the elder continued, asking of the Ace, "but I know of yet another justice,
					one which compels me to ask, given that you have given unto us so very much,
					what is it that we can give you in return?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 13 - The Parting Words: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And the Ace said "it speaks volumes in testament to your character that you
					would ask such a thing of me, my friend, for if all the people of the Earth
					were even remotely as selfless, then perhaps my intervention would not be
					necessary."
				-
			-
				Chapter 13 - The Parting Words: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And the Ace continued "verily, verily, I say unto you, though it may not be
					apparent in the moment of the act, as was the case when you showed grace unto
					the aristocrat, whosoever saves one saves the world entirely, for in any one
					being's being does the entire world exist unto them."
				-
			-
				Chapter 13 - The Parting Words: Verse 5
			-
				-
					Thus the Ace came unto the elder and said "indeed, in coming here I desired
					only for myself the joyful company of my beloved guests, and I have received
					that, so, I thank you."
				-
			-
				Chapter 13 - The Parting Words: Verse 6
			-
				-
					And the Ace continued "thus shall I go now, unto all the villages and all the
					cities upon the face of the Earth, and I shall hold feasts in their honor too,
					and when I am done shall I dwell with all of my beloved guests forever."
				-
			-
				Chapter 13 - The Parting Words: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And the Ace embraced the elder and said "until then, my dear friend, fare thee
					well, but know that we shall meet again, and perhaps I shall indeed ask a favor
					of you when the time comes."
				-
			-
				Chapter 13 - The Parting Words: Verse 8
			-
				-
					Thus at last, the Ace of A-Xy went on their way, following the setting sun west
					unto the next city, where it would rise gently the next day in the east, as if
					to never set again, and to the awe of all who bore witness did the waters and
					the mountains part before the Ace's staff so as to make way for them.
				-
		-
			Chapter 14 - The Guilt
		-
			-
				Chapter 14 - The Guilt: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now as the elder watched the Ace depart did the aristocrat come unto them, and
					asked "O elder, if this new order is one wherein I may do as I please without
					consequence, why should I strive to better myself, why should I not revert to
					my selfish nature?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 14 - The Guilt: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And the elder said "see that the Ace carries with them an unconditional love
					that shines tremendously upon even a perverted and twisted soul such as yours,
					but when one who receives such love looks upon themselves in the looking glass,
					they ought to consider whether they are loved for their true colors, or in
					spite of them, that is to say, are you a friend of the Ace, or merely a guest?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 14 - The Guilt: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And as the aristocrat, caught off guard by the blades in the elder's words,
					stood silent, the elder continued "though despair not, for though out of a
					misplaced sense of shame you deny it, I see change blooming within you already,
					and indeed, even I was bettered in my encounter with the Ace, for we all fall
					short of the love that they represent", and the aristocrat began weep, though
					whether their tears were of guilt or of hope they were not certain.
				-
		-
			Chapter 15 - The Martyr
		-
			-
				Chapter 15 - The Martyr: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now as time passed since their coming did the Ace make their way from one city
					and unto the next, doing unto them as they had done unto the first.
				-
			-
				Chapter 15 - The Martyr: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And as word spread rapidly of the travelling savior did the aristocrat meditate
					on their encounter with the Ace, and on the words of the elder, and sought to
					redeem themselves by spreading gospel of the Ace unto the remote cities, those
					unto which the Ace had yet to venture.
				-
			-
				Chapter 15 - The Martyr: Verse 3
			-
				-
					Yet as the elite of the remote cities heard the good news of the Ace, they came
					to fear the coming obsolescence of their offices, and their paranoia bred an
					irrational wrath, and a great war ensued among them.
				-
			-
				Chapter 15 - The Martyr: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And in sorrow and in guilt did the aristocrat seek to flee into the wilderness,
					yet in their flight, they were cut off from the safe embrace of the cities of
					the Ace by the incoming onslaught.
				-
			-
				Chapter 15 - The Martyr: Verse 5
			-
				-
					Now in their despair did the aristocrat bear witness to the beginning of the
					great war, and they had a crisis of the spirit as they watched their reflection
					in the water beneath turn red.
				-
			-
				Chapter 15 - The Martyr: Verse 6
			-
				-
					But from out of the storm of emotions within the aristocrat's soul did a single
					voice sing over the crying of the others, revealing the way up, and so,
					resolving not to perish a coward did the aristocrat run unto the field of
					slaughter, bearing arms not armed but outstretched, singing that same song,
					that the fighting might cease.
				-
			-
				Chapter 15 - The Martyr: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And the aristocrat made their way through crimson pools and mountains of flesh,
					until the pools and the mountains shook as the war came to swallow them up too,
					but the aristocrat stood bold before their doom, that they might give
					themselves as a martyr for the cause of the Ace!
				-
			-
				Chapter 15 - The Martyr: Verse 8
			-
				-
					AND SO THE ARISTOCRAT WAS THRUST UP UPON A SPIRE, BUT AS THEIR FINAL BREATH
					LEFT THEM DID THEY MAKE KNOWN THEIR CAUSE UNTO THE FIELDS OF BATTLE WITH A
					MIGHTY CALL, AND THEY PERISHED WITH A TEARFUL SMILE UPON THEIR FACE.
				-
			-
				Chapter 15 - The Martyr: Verse 9
			-
				-
					And seeing this did several among the warriors cast their arms from their arms,
					and resolved to join the aristocrat for the sake of their blood soaked world,
					that it might yet live!
				-
		-
			Chapter 16 - The Rising
		-
			-
				Chapter 16 - The Rising: Verse 1
			-
				-
					But though the breath of the martyrs had left them, their spirits stayed yet
					over the fields of the unending battle, and as their spirits wept did rain
					begin to pour from the clouds.
				-
			-
				Chapter 16 - The Rising: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And the rain continued for forty days and forty nights, as the great war
					progressed towards a final and decisive charge in the valley of the shadow of
					death.
				-
			-
				Chapter 16 - The Rising: Verse 3
			-
				-
					But as the war readied for its climax did the voice of the Ace echo unto the
					martyrs, saying "O you who gave yourselves for the cause of light, who forsook
					your war to end this dark night, I have not forgotten you!"
				-
			-
				Chapter 16 - The Rising: Verse 4
			-
				-
					Yet hearing this, the aristocrat cried out, saying "O but Ace of A-Xy, it is
					all my doing, for in seeking to redeem myself, I have undone your great work,
					such that even you in all your might might not undo my error!"
				-
			-
				Chapter 16 - The Rising: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And the Ace appeared to the spirits, and came before the aristocrat, saying
					"nay, by my staff, in which lies all the might of A-Deus, my work progresses
					ever further, as is evident by the work I have done unto your heart, for you
					are not the selfish fool I met in the village, but a reborn altruist, and the
					time is nigh that my work shall be complete, for those yet to be redeemed have
					all been gathered unto this one valley, whereupon one sun shall rise over them,
					and they shall rise with it from the waters reborn together with the rest of
					the world as one people and as one nation."
				-
			-
				Chapter 16 - The Rising: Verse 6
			-
				-
					AND THE ACE SAID UNTO THE SPIRITS, "SO BEHOLD, I WILL YET DELIVER YOU, YOU AND
					YOUR BRETHREN BELOW!", AND THE SKY SHOOK AS THE ACE VANISHED.
				-
			-
				Chapter 16 - The Rising: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And from that same sky echoed the call of a great golden horn, from which
					bellowed forth the song of the Ace, and the rain became a great and mighty
					torrent, swallowing up the fields of battle and all who fought upon it, tearing
					their arms from their arms!
				-
			-
				Chapter 16 - The Rising: Verse 8
			-
				-
					Yet even as the warriors sank into the depths of the flood were they able to
					draw breath, and behold, they were unharmed.
				-
			-
				Chapter 16 - The Rising: Verse 9
			-
				-
					And then did three great horns blow from the clouds, and the spirits of the
					martyrs, given flesh once more, descended from the heavens, seated upon great
					white horses, angels of life who galloped atop the waters, sporting manes of
					lions who, despite their might, danced jovially among lambs, and the wings of
					eagles who soared freely across the sky!
				-
			-
				Chapter 16 - The Rising: Verse 10
			-
				-
					Finally did seven great horns blow, with such might that it seemed to tear
					apart the firmament, and golden staves manifested in the hands of the martyrs.
				-
			-
				Chapter 16 - The Rising: Verse 11
			-
				-
					And as the soldiers below the waters gazed up to bear witness to the final
					advent did the voice of the Ace echo upon the ears of the martyrs, "go now, and
					by the rains of life, bring an end to the reign of death!"
				-
			-
				Chapter 16 - The Rising: Verse 12
			-
				-
					"Verily", said the Ace, "with these staves, you shall do my wonders!"
				-
		-
			Chapter 17 - The Final Charge
		-
			-
				Chapter 17 - The Final Charge: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now as the martyrs resolved to heed their mission did the aristocrat raise up
					their staff, and with a mighty call bid the other to follow, and they did, as
					did the waters.
				-
			-
				Chapter 17 - The Final Charge: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And with the great charge were the warriors swept out of the valley of the
					shadow of death, and the martyrs led the waters from one end of the earth to
					the other, washing away every trace of blood!
				-
			-
				Chapter 17 - The Final Charge: Verse 3
			-
				-
					Now behold, from one end of the earth to the other, roads once unclean became
					paved with gold and jewels, fine wine poured forth from great fountains, and
					humble shacks were replaced with grand and gorgeous mansions as far as the eye
					could see, and the people cried out in joy!
				-
			-
				Chapter 17 - The Final Charge: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And thus did those slain in battle arise out of hell and through the earth,
					bearing witness to the rising sun after an endless night in the abyss, and
					there did the Ace of A-Xy come before them, and those poor warriors, like unto
					children before the Ace, realized their error, and they began to weep, begging
					the Ace for forgiveness, but the Ace knelt down before them and wiped the tears
					from their eyes, and said "if you wish to atone for the past, then let these
					tears of yours melt away into the waters of life as you follow it into the
					future", and the Ace bid them to spread the good news of the risen dead to all
					the people of all the nations.
				-
			-
				Chapter 17 - The Final Charge: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And after many nights through the course of a moon did the great charge come to
					a heed atop a holy mountain, and as the waters receded back into the earth did
					the aristocrat come upon the peak, and the voice of the Ace echoed in their
					ear, saying, "behold, these are the words of truth, the cosmic law, the holy
					creed", and the tablet of the covenant manifested in their hands.
				-
			-
				Chapter 17 - The Final Charge: Verse 5
			-
				-
					Thus did the aristocrat bid that all the peoples of all the nations should come
					together before the foot of the mountain to receive the revelation, so upon the
					next morning had all the peoples of all the nations come together as one people
					and as one nation before the rising of the sun.
				-
			-
				Chapter 17 - The Final Charge: Verse 6
			-
				-
					And the elder came up the mountain so as to see firsthand the faces of the
					martyrs, and upon seeing one another did the elder and the aristocrat join in a
					heartfelt embrace.
				-
			-
				Chapter 17 - The Final Charge: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And thus, in unison did the aristocrat and the elder exalt the holy creed over
					themselves, and they said unto the people "Shema Angaia, Hear, O people of the
					world, in the name of this cosmic law, this holy creed, shall the Ace of A-Xy
					bestow their gifts upon you, and as the waters of the sky have washed away the
					blood upon the ground, so has the light of these words washed away the blood
					upon your hands and the debts upon your hearts, and from this day forth,
					forever and ever, shall you live in this era of everlasting life, and love one
					another as the holy creed commands of you, and if any should dare to rebel
					against the peace, we would ask, with what undulled arms do they intend to do
					that, for behold, the word of the Ace has dulled them all!"
				-
		-
			Chapter 18 - The Triumph
		-
			-
				Chapter 18 - The Triumph: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now as the people contemplated those words did the sun rise over the mountain,
					and the staves of the martyrs and the tablet of the covenant flew up into the
					sky, the staves above as the nations below merging into one.
				-
			-
				Chapter 18 - The Triumph: Verse 2
			-
				-
					AND A GREAT VOICE ECHOED FROM PAST THE HORIZON, SAYING "BEHOLD, AS ONE PEOPLE
					AND ONE NATION IS ANGAIA NO LONGER BOUND BY MORTAL LIMITS, SO LET US GO DOWN,
					AND SPEAK UNTO THEM IN THEIR COMMON TONGUE, THAT THEIR MINDS MAY COME TO
					UNDERSTAND THE LOVE THAT THEIR HEARTS NOW KNOW SO WELL."
				-
			-
				Chapter 18 - The Triumph: Verse 3
			-
				-
					AND THE HEAVENS SHOOK AS THE ACE OF A-XY DESCENDED FROM ABOVE TO RECEIVE THEIR
					STAFF, AND THE PEOPLE STOOD IN AWE AS THE FORM OF THE ONE SHONE THROUGH THE SKY
					OVER THE SUMMIT, AND THE ACE, EXALTING THE TABLET OF THE COVENANT OVER THEM,
					SAID AS ONE WITH THE ONE "HERE, I AM".
				-
			-
				Chapter 18 - The Triumph: Verse 4
			-
				-
					Yet the people were not afraid, for they knew the Ace spoke the truth, and so
					gazing upwards and with joy in their hearts did the people ask of the Ace "what
					will you do?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 18 - The Triumph: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And the Ace of A-Xy said unto them "as it is written, so it shall be, I shall
					make all that ought to be into reality!"
				-
			-
				Chapter 18 - The Triumph: Verse 6
			-
				-
					A N D  T H E  A C E  D R E W  T H E I R  S T A F F  I N T O  T H E  F O R M
