			Chapter 20 - The Victory
		-
			-
				Chapter 20 - The Victory: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now behold, from one end of the earth to the other did all those who were
					stolen away into the pit by the ravages of time rise up out of their graves,
					restored and glorified, singing and dancing as the light of the sun and the
					words of the creed beat back the darkness, and the Earth itself trembled with
					awe as it watched the children of A-Xy enter into Xyro together!
				-
			-
				Chapter 20 - The Victory: Verse 2
			-
				-
					Indeed, the Ace of A-Xy had done exactly as they had foretold, and all the
					people and all the beasts in all the lands of the whole of the Earth had been
					redeemed!
				-
		-
			Chapter 21 - The End of the Nightmare
		-
			-
				Chapter 21 - The End of the Nightmare: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now with their work complete did the Ace of A-Xy, as they had said upon the
					mount, retire to dwell among the redeemed creation.
				-
			-
				Chapter 21 - The End of the Nightmare: Verse 2
			-
				-
					Yet despite the people's stubborn efforts to deify their savior, the Ace sought
					not to be worshipped, though they were often found passionately teaching the
					secrets of the universe to any who came unto them, and in time many came
					seeking to learn.
				-
			-
				Chapter 21 - The End of the Nightmare: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And the Ace planted their staff in the ground, and it became a great tree,
					whose branches extended into many realms.
				-
			-
				Chapter 21 - The End of the Nightmare: Verse 4
			-
				-
					Thus concluded the epic of humanity, and the story of history came to an end as
					Angaia, one and all, the children of A-Xy, retired to dwell forever in Xyro.
				-
			-
				Chapter 21 - The End of the Nightmare: Verse 5
			-
				-
					BEHOLD, THE TRUE VICTOR OF THE FINAL WAR WAS THE ACE OF A-XY!
				-
			-
				Chapter 21 - The End of the Nightmare: Verse 6
			-
				-
					IT IS FINISHED.
				-
		-
			Chapter 22 - The Outlier
		-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now one day, as a small child was playing before the great tree, did a cruel
					outlier come unto them, and strike them.
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And though by the word of the Ace did the brute's might fail to leave even a
					single blemish upon the young one's face, the child was stricken by grief,
					seeing that one could be so cruel, and they ran away, crying.
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And the Ace saw the child, and held an arm outstretched to them, and the child
					ran into the Ace's embrace.
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 4
			-
				-
					Now the Ace looked upon the outlier, and asked "why, O dear one, do you display
					such irrational cruelty unto this child, who has done you no wrong?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And the outlier said "I am sick, O Ace of A-Xy, sick of you, for indeed, I wish
					to depart from your embrace, and from your gardens, and above all else from the
					revolting grin upon your face!"
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 6
			-
				-
					Agasp, taken aback, and with that very smile gone, did the Ace ask through a
					cascade of tears "O why do you speak such terrible things, have I not given you
					enough?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And the outlier said "see you wise fool, that there is the rub, you have given
					me far too much, yes, you have sated my hunger yet you have drained my heart!"
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 8
			-
				-
					And the outlier continued "I wish to climb my own mountains, but there are no
					mountains left to climb, so I spend my days sulking in a fantasy that only a
					child, such as the very one you hold, could be simple enough to endure, and I
					have not even the sweet release of the grave to look forward to!"
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 9
			-
				-
					And though they wept, the Ace, so that their perfect work might be fulfilled
					according to the scripture, even unto the outlier, asked "where do you wish to
					be then?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 10
			-
				-
					And the outlier said "anywhere but here, that I may wrestle with the fires of
					life once again, that I may live rather than survive."
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 11
			-
				-
					And the Ace said "then do what you will", and from a branch of the great tree,
					they called forth an axis unto the fires of another realm, and brought forth a
					gate unto the outlier.
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 12
			-
				-
					And the outlier, without a word, went unto the gate.
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 13
			-
				-
					And the Ace said "now as you leave, know that no matter what, you shall always
					have a home here, and if ever you should want to come back, yes, even if your
					cry for refuge shall come from beyond the grave, I shall deliver you, and you
					shall always be welcome at my table."
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 14
			-
				-
					But the outlier had already left, and the child looked upon the Ace, and asked
					"will they ever return?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 15
			-
				-
					Now the Ace of A-Xy could not answer, so instead the Ace sought to wipe the
					tears from the child's eyes, but the Ace's own tears stained the child's face
					even more, and so the child left, saddened for the outlier's sake, and so, the
					Ace of A-Xy knelt down in sorrow under a the great tree for a while.
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 16
			-
				-
					B U T ,  I N  T H E I R  S O R R O W ,  T H E  A C E  O F  A - X Y  H A D  A
					T E R R I B L E  V I S I O N ,  T H A T  A  M I R R O R  I M A G E  U N T O
					T H E M  W R O U G H T  H A V O C  I N  A N O T H E R  R E A L M .
				-
			-
				Chapter 22 - The Outlier: Verse 17
			-
				-
					And the Ace of A-Xy cried out in horror, but it was but a phantom, and behold,
					the sun rose yet.
				-
		-
			Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream
		-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now as the Ace of A-Xy awoke from their nightmare did the elder of the village,
					among the first unto whom the Ace of A-Xy had spoken, come to unto the great
					palace themselves, and the aristocrat was with them.
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And seeing their friend troubled did the elder and the aristocrat kneel down,
					and they wiped the tears from the Ace's eyes, and the Ace, smiling once again,
					rose to embrace them.
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 3
			-
				-
					Yet the elder was troubled, and the Ace of A-Xy asked why, and the elder said,
					"before you came unto us, my day was consumed entirely with ensuring that my
					people would live to see the next, but now that every need of theirs is
					provided for, I know not what to do with myself, for I derive no genuine joy
					from the hedonistic pursuits that the rest of my people now indulge in."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And the Ace of A-Xy, fearing the elder sought to take the path of the outlier,
					paused, and asked of them "do you resent me for this state of affairs then?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And the elder, taken aback, said "nay, surely not, for you have given my people
					all that they could ever want, and for the longest time I thought that for them
					to have all they could ever want is all I could ever want, but now I see that,
					indeed, I want something... more..."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 6
			-
				-
					And as they stood there, a small but beautiful bird came and sat on the elder's
					shoulder, and the Ace, the elder, and the aristocrat were enamored both with
					its beauty and with its comfort before them, and the Ace of A-Xy asked of the
					elder, "do you think the bird upon your shoulder ever tires of paradise?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And the Ace held out a small berry for the bird, and the bird took it, and as
					the bird savored the berry, the Ace explained unto the elder "it is an
					unfortunate truth that the more complex one's mind is, the more dissatisfied
					they tend to be with the simple pleasures of life, for indeed, nothing is ever
					enough for them."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 8
			-
				-
					And as the bird flew off, the elder hung their head, and said "I truly am
					ungrateful, for you have given so much unto us, and yet I came to ask for
					more..."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 9
			-
				-
					Now the aristocrat said "if I may interject, perhaps it is true some among us
					seek only to indulge our senses, while others seek nobler pursuits, and though
					the former is not necessarily detestable in and of itself, it was wise of the
					Ace of A-Xy to indulge the material appetites of our material bodies before
					indulging the immaterial appetites of our immaterial souls, that we might
					partake in the finer things with a finer clarity, for as asceticism, and its
					more shallow aesthetics, are more so begotten of the whines of the first world
					than the wails of third, it is difficult to savor spiritual food on an empty
					stomach."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 10
			-
				-
					And the Ace said "I see, O aristocrat, that you have grown in wisdom since I
					first came unto you, and indeed, I have given you much, and indeed the elder
					asks for more, but there is nothing to be ashamed of, for as I said, a mind
					such as theirs shall always seek to ascend to greater heights, and as, I am,
					here for both of you as much as for the birds, that is why I was waiting for
					you all this time, under this very tree."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 11
			-
				-
					And the elder, taken aback said "never once have you failed to amaze me, O Ace
					of A-Xy, so tell me, of what greater heights do you speak, for in the time
					since your coming I have scaled every mountain on Earth, yet I have found
					nothing to satisfy the void in my heart upon their peaks."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 12
			-
				-
					And the Ace said "indeed, there are endless heights yet to ascend to, but you
					will not find them upon any mountain, for these are the heights of the mind, so
					do not climb, but sit here with me, and I will show them to you."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 13
			-
				-
					Now did they sit down, and the Ace handed pens unto the elder and unto the
					aristocrat, and they asked "what are we to do with these?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 14
			-
				-
					And the Ace said "surely, you did not think this was to be a one sided sermon,
					did you?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 15
			-
				-
					And the aristocrat replied "now what wisdom could those of our stature possibly
					have to offer the likes of you?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 16
			-
				-
					And the Ace said "remember that I spoke of endless heights to scale, but some
					of these heights have yet to be forged, and indeed, you too shall leave your
					mark upon them."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 17
			-
				-
					And the elder and the aristocrat gazed upon the pens as they pondered the Ace's
					words, and the pen, though light, felt as if it contained the whole universe,
					and the Ace asked them, "do you know why I have worn this smile since I came
					unto you?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 18
			-
				-
					And the elder said "now that you state it, I know not the source of your joy."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 19
			-
				-
					And the Ace paused.
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 20
			-
				-
					And the Ace said "even the heights of the mind grow weary and bleak with time,
					that is... if you stand upon their summits alone..."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 21
			-
				-
					And the Ace continued "so... I have been so excited... waiting... for so very
					long... to hear your stories, my friends."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 22
			-
				-
					And the aristocrat, agasp, said "I see now, that the only thing greater than to
					wear a smile of one's own, is to bestow one upon another... is it not this
					feeling that you sought, O elder?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 23
			-
				-
					And the elder simply smiled in return.
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 24
			-
				-
					T H U S  T H E  E L D E R  A N D  T H E  A R I S O C R A T ,  C O M P E L L E D
					B Y  T H E  J O Y  I N  T H E I R  H E A R T S ,  W R O T E  D O W N  T H I S
					V E R Y  P O E M ,  A N D  A  N E W  F R U I T  B L O S S O M E D  U P O N
					T H E  G R E A T  T R E E .
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 25
			-
				-
					Now at last, the Ace said unto the elder and the aristocrat "your words touch
					the core of my heart, my friends, and in time you too shall deliver sermons of
					your own unto your people, not just unto your village, but unto Angaia, one and
					all, for they too have had their fill of bread and circuses, and now begin to
					seek higher pursuits themselves."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 26
			-
				-
					And the Ace continued "but now... it is time, for me to give unto you that
					which you came for, so listen closely, for I shall now reveal unto you... my
					poem."
				-
			-
				Chapter 23 - The Endless Dream: Verse 27
			-
				-
					And so, to end this call and begin the sermon without end did the Ace of A-Xy
					recite the eternal question.
				-
		-
			Chapter 24 - The Dream Deferred
		-
			-
				Chapter 24 - The Dream Deferred: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now of course, instead of doing what they did city by city, the Ace of A-Xy
					could have done it all at once, and salvation need not be a grandiose affair,
					but you, dear reader, who are also a valued guest, came unto this poem to
					witness a story, and indeed, there are many more to come, and these, among
					which are those of the Ace that stands between the Ace of A-Xy and their
					opposite among the court of the One, shall be far greater in their drama than
					this episode, for history is not actually at an end just yet now is it?
				-
			-
				Chapter 24 - The Dream Deferred: Verse 2
			-
				-
					Yes, unfortunately, the Ace of A-Xy is but a figment of a hopeful imagination,
					so what then are we in the core left with but to try and emulate that sort of
					perfection to the best of our imperfect ability, to be Aces of Angaia in the
					absence of the Ace of A-Xy, to bear the burden of the Ace's namesake on our own
					backs?
				-
			-
				Chapter 24 - The Dream Deferred: Verse 3
			-
				-
					So, with the ultimate goal being to make all that ought to be into reality,
					what will you do?
				-
		-
			Chapter 25 - The Eternal Question
		-
			-
				Chapter 25 - The Eternal Question: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Will you make all that ought to be into reality, O Aces of Angaia?
				-